stylometry: One type of probability distribution is skewed v. symmetric.  A symmetric distribution is when the left side of the point on the distribution scale is symmetric to the right side of the distribution scale.  When it is not symmetric it is skewed.  When the left side of the scale is skewed it is NEGATIVELY skewed and when the right side of the scale is skewed it is POSITIVELY skewed.  When a class takes a test on a 100 pt. scale it will be negatively skewed because the students who perform poorly on the test will pull the curve down.  When people are waiting in line at a bank, it will be an example of a positive skew on the distribution scale because there are people who will take two minutes to be helped and then there are people who may make 15 minutes to be helped so there will be a variation on the scale.
